obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9832822680473328, "span": {"begin": 417, "end": 421}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:25555"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "N", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.990980327129364, "span": {"begin": 427, "end": 428}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:79792"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GSDMD", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9916021227836609, "span": {"begin": 456, "end": 461}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3553"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL1B", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9964274764060974, "span": {"begin": 556, "end": 560}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL18", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9963034391403198, "span": {"begin": 565, "end": 569}}], "text": "Pyroptosis is an inflammatory form of programmed cell death. Pore-forming protein gasdermins (GSDM) are crucial factors for pyroptosis execution whereby GSDMD and GSDME are most deeply studied [1]. Pyroptosis is initiated through inflammasome activation resulting to activation of caspase-1 (CASP1). Active CASP1 cleaves GSDMD, and also cleaves and thus activates pro-inflammatory cytokines interleukin-1B (IL1B) and IL18 [2]. N-terminal cleaved domain of GSDMD forms pores in the plasma membrane leading to cell swelling and pyroptotic cell death [3, 4]. IL1B and IL18 are released through the pores contributing to inflammatory and pyroptotic processes.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:53:05 +0000 2026"}